","category_name":null,"category_rank":null,"individual_id":"019d0a11-4d30-7112-ab4b-561aafee688a","metric_summary":null,"competitor_name":"Jennifer Castelluccio","competitor_type":"individual","additional_course":false,"affiliation_labels":[]}],"course_id":"019d0f21-2179-7f7d-84f5-c160df6140f3","course_name":"Short Advanced","distance_km":null,"result_count":18,"control_count":null,"course_climb_m":null}],"event_id":"019b81f3-1f4e-7709-a6e5-9c5a02b44584","venue_id":"019b820a-0440-79c9-a2de-f6a11d17ad0f","event_date":"2018-06-09","event_kind":"race","event_name":"Ultimate Orienteer #6 - Middle - Jack & Indian","venue_name":"Jack & Indian","event_notes":null,"course_count":4,"event_status":null,"result_count":73,"citation_count":3,"event_comments":"Thank You All Volunteers!\n\nPart of the Ultimate Orienteer Series, COC’s variety pack of orienteering events.\nWe’ll be using Forest Runs’ Jack & Indian Creek map for Day 1 of a 2-day weekend in Eastern Washington. Stay for Sunday’s Goat at the legendary Salmon La Sac.\nThe Indian/Jack Creek map covers lower hills in Eastern Cascades north of Cle Elum. Further north, the hills quickly turn into steep mountains, culminating with Mount Stuart roughly half the way between Cle Elum and Leavenworth.\nThe map terrain is similar to Teanaway but hillier, and all the courses have quite a bit of climb, most of it in the first 1/3 of the courses. After that, it is more downhill navigation with occasional upward legs. The hilliness makes the terrain physically demanding, and numerous valleys, spurs, and a few ancient landslides also offer quite a bit of navigational challenge. You have to traverse slopes broken with numerous valleys, slow down to fine-read pockets of complex terrain, and recognize features in green (dense) forests.\nAll the courses stay in forest, ranging from wide open pine forests, offering gorgeous views, till hard-to-penetrate undergrowth on watercourses and humid valleys. Parts of the area has been logged a decade or so ago, resulting in grassy open landscape. The former logging roads and tracks are partly overgrown. These are mostly mapped and offer quite a bit of help in moving across the terrain, but smaller, indistinct trails may be hard to recognize. There are also a large number of animal tracks, not mapped in most cases, but will help you quite a bit if you hit one that moves in the right direction. Root-stocks are mapped as green X (not brown).\nThere is usually a myriad of narrow passes in-between brush and undergrowth, so dry green areas are typically not hard to get through. (This may not be true for humid green areas!) There is a larger crossable marsh near the start, and several small marshy spots in the valleys.\nSafety bearing: move west until you hit the paved road (North Fork Teanaway Road). Then head north to the campground.","external_links":[{"link_url":"https://cascadeoc.org/event/ultimate-orienteer-6-middle/","link_type":"event_page"},{"link_url":"https://cascadeoc.org/map/jack-indian/","link_type":"map"},{"link_url":"http://rg.cascadeoc.org/rg2/#217","link_type":"routegadget"},{"link_url":"http://cascadeoc.org/series/ultimate-orienteer/","link_type":"series"},{"link_url":"https://cascadeoc.org/series/ultimate-orienteer/","link_type":"series"},{"link_url":"http://obasen.orientering.se/winsplits/online/en/default.asp?page=classes&databaseId=56150","link_type":"splits"},{"link_url":"https://cascadeoc.org/season/ultimate-season-standings-18/","link_type":"standings"}],"volunteer_roles":[{"role_name":"Control Pickup","individual_id":"019d0a11-4d30-7501-b90e-0beb7cb865cc","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Kate Byers","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Control Pickup","individual_id":"019d0a11-4d30-710f-b42f-ecba537a7836","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Ott Toomet","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Control Pickup","individual_id":"019d0a11-4d30-7324-93c0-9bbb71d5ef2c","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Rebecca Jensen","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Control Pickup","individual_id":"019b7fed-a88a-7e76-b17a-062d4b2ada0c","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Rolf Kuestner","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Control Pickup","individual_id":"019b7b13-3219-7a2c-93f7-0d0d45e15e8e","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Sue Kuestner","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Course Designer","individual_id":"019d0a11-4d30-710f-b42f-ecba537a7836","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Ott Toomet","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Course Designer(s)","individual_id":"019d0a11-4d30-710f-b42f-ecba537a7836","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Ott Toomet","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Epunch","individual_id":"01913919-da03-757e-b829-aa2bdc684400","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Debbie Newell","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Epunch","individual_id":"019d0a11-4d2f-736d-863f-5e546e61e969","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Ing Uhlin","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Epunch Coordinator","individual_id":"019d0a11-4d2f-736d-863f-5e546e61e969","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Ing Uhlin","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Finish","individual_id":"019d0a11-4d2f-7807-bdc6-77a7e939a3ae","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Eric Jones","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Meet Director","individual_id":"019d0a40-c419-799a-97ec-c9f1967b2d4c","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Bob Stratton","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Meet Director","individual_id":"019b815e-cce3-782c-b020-2b625672abe6","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Robert Stratton","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Registration","individual_id":"01913919-da03-757e-b829-aa2bdc684400","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Debbie Newell","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Registration","individual_id":"019d0a40-c41e-7a34-abef-8e18a2195001","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Pam MacRae","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Start","individual_id":"019b811c-3e18-7e4f-84b5-4159730958fb","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Pat Kelly","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null}],"organizing_club_id":"01912f3e-e3e1-7e8e-b3c6-32387a8b4990","result_source_brief":"Web Snapshot: https://cocwebsite.azurewebsites.net/result/ultimate-orienteer-6-middle-jack-indian-creeks/","organizing_club_name":"Cascade Orienteering Club","cumulative_event_comments":"Thank You All Volunteers!\n\nPart of the Ultimate Orienteer Series, COC’s variety pack of orienteering events.\nWe’ll be using Forest Runs’ Jack & Indian Creek map for Day 1 of a 2-day weekend in Eastern Washington. Stay for Sunday’s Goat at the legendary Salmon La Sac.\nThe Indian/Jack Creek map covers lower hills in Eastern Cascades north of Cle Elum. Further north, the hills quickly turn into steep mountains, culminating with Mount Stuart roughly half the way between Cle Elum and Leavenworth.\nThe map terrain is similar to Teanaway but hillier, and all the courses have quite a bit of climb, most of it in the first 1/3 of the courses. After that, it is more downhill navigation with occasional upward legs. The hilliness makes the terrain physically demanding, and numerous valleys, spurs, and a few ancient landslides also offer quite a bit of navigational challenge. You have to traverse slopes broken with numerous valleys, slow down to fine-read pockets of complex terrain, and recognize features in green (dense) forests.\nAll the courses stay in forest, ranging from wide open pine forests, offering gorgeous views, till hard-to-penetrate undergrowth on watercourses and humid valleys. Parts of the area has been logged a decade or so ago, resulting in grassy open landscape. The former logging roads and tracks are partly overgrown. These are mostly mapped and offer quite a bit of help in moving across the terrain, but smaller, indistinct trails may be hard to recognize. There are also a large number of animal tracks, not mapped in most cases, but will help you quite a bit if you hit one that moves in the right direction. Root-stocks are mapped as green X (not brown).\nThere is usually a myriad of narrow passes in-between brush and undergrowth, so dry green areas are typically not hard to get through. (This may not be true for humid green areas!) There is a larger crossable marsh near the start, and several small marshy spots in the valleys.\nSafety bearing: move west until you hit the paved road (North Fork Teanaway Road). Then head north to the campground."}
